00:29:36,920 --> 00:29:40,960
But to get to 65%,
you gotta go through that?


501
00:29:40,960 --> 00:29:42,640
Sometimes, yeah.


502
00:29:47,200 --> 00:29:50,600
Can I see components, the blades?


503
00:29:59,280 --> 00:30:00,840
Oh, what is that?


504
00:30:02,160 --> 00:30:04,600
It's a crack...in this blade.


505
00:30:06,200 --> 00:30:07,720
There's an obvious crack.


506
00:30:16,880 --> 00:30:18,400
Yeah.


507
00:30:18,400 --> 00:30:20,680
The blades often get those
after a flight,


508
00:30:20,680 --> 00:30:23,320
but that's not
a flight safety problem.


509
00:30:23,320 --> 00:30:26,600
Well, what is it, then?
We were told to log it
as a maintenance problem.


510
00:30:26,600 --> 00:30:30,400
Only if it develops into a full
fracture, THAT would be a failure.


511
00:30:30,400 --> 00:30:33,240
So a failure only happens
if it actually shears off?


512
00:30:33,240 --> 00:30:34,280
Uh-huh.


513
00:30:35,720 --> 00:30:39,080
Bull! The failure is the crack.


514
00:30:39,080 --> 00:30:40,680
Well, you could argue that...


515
00:30:40,680 --> 00:30:44,000
The failure is the crack - I mean,
because it's not in the design.


516
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:46,600
You know and I know
it's not supposed to crack.


517
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:52,880
Who has the rest of the test data?


518
00:30:56,560 --> 00:30:57,920
Is that it?


